2. **[^](#cite_ref-4)** Including [Windows](/wiki/Windows), [Linux](/wiki/Linux), [macOS](/wiki/MacOS), [FreeBSD](/wiki/FreeBSD), [NetBSD](/wiki/NetBSD), and [Illumos](/wiki/Illumos). Host build tools on [Android](/wiki/Android_(operating_system)), [iOS](/wiki/IOS), [Haiku](/wiki/Haiku_(operating_system)), [Redox](/wiki/Redox_(operating_system)), and [Fuchsia](/wiki/Fuchsia_(operating_system)) are not officially shipped; these operating systems are supported as targets. [&#91; 2 &#93;](#cite_note-CrossPlatform-2)
3. **[^](#cite_ref-7)** Third-party dependencies, e.g., [LLVM](/wiki/LLVM) or [MSVC](/wiki/MSVC), are subject to their own licenses. [&#91; 3 &#93;](#cite_note-5) [&#91; 4 &#93;](#cite_note-licenses-6)
4. ^ [***a***](#cite_ref-nil_10-0) [***b***](#cite_ref-nil_10-1) NIL is cited as an influence for Rust in multiple sources; this likely refers to Network Implementation Language developed by Robert Strom and others at [IBM](/wiki/IBM), which pioneered [typestate analysis](/wiki/Typestate_analysis), [&#91; 5 &#93;](#cite_note-Strom1983-8) [&#91; 6 &#93;](#cite_note-9) not to be confused with [New Implementation of LISP](/wiki/NIL_(programming_language)).
